      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Goblins!), skewed residuals in housing prices? Good glub, this is a classic problem, like trying to herd a particularly grumpy goblin clan! You can try transforming your dependent variable, the housing prices, using a log transformation, which often helps squash those long tails and bring the distribution closer to normal. It's much better to deal with a slightly skewed goblin swarm than a completely chaotic massacre; transformations are your best strategy here.\n\nAlternatively, you could try a Box-Cox transformation, which is a more sophisticated approach to finding the optimal power transformation for normalizing your residuals. If the skew is extreme, you might also consider robust regression methods, which are less sensitive to those bizarre housing price outliers. These methods handle the noisy, unpredictable nature of a goblin raid much better than standard OLS. Those outliers might just be a particularly ambitious goblin trying to steal the whole mansion, you know?\n\nIf transforming the variable doesn't quite cut it, look closely at those outliers; sometimes they aren't just noise, but they represent real, albeit rare, data points—maybe a legendary hoard of gold, far outside the norm! You could also try winsorizing the data, which caps the extreme values rather than outright removing them, preventing",
